The paper focuses on grasp selection for manipulation tasks, which is a core problem in robotics. The paper discusses the use of a previously proposed manipulation metric and evaluates its performance in two-step manipulation tasks. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of artificial intelligence techniques for grasp selection, which suggests that it could also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also mentions computer vision techniques for grasp selection, which suggests that it could belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper presents quantitative results and evaluates the practicality of the approach on a physical robot manipulator, which suggests that it could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of constraints in manipulation tasks, which suggests that it could also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
